1
00:00:11,200 --> 00:00:13,640
Come on, Albert!

2
00:00:54,520 --> 00:00:57,639
Mickey Bricks, if you've
ever been brilliant,

3
00:00:57,640 --> 00:00:59,240
please be brilliant now.

4
00:01:21,400 --> 00:01:26,440
Gentlemen! I know what
you're thinking...but, er...

5
00:02:11,000 --> 00:02:13,159
I guess...

6
00:02:13,160 --> 00:02:16,399
most of you must
have thought that...

7
00:02:16,400 --> 00:02:18,880
one day it would end like this...

8
00:03:08,679 --> 00:03:11,879
sync and corrections by Bellows
www.addic7ed.com

9
00:03:13,480 --> 00:03:15,699
- Oh, you did not just say that!
- It is a well known fact.

10
00:03:15,700 --> 00:03:17,260
- Well known by who?
- Everyone. - Not me.

11
00:03:17,261 --> 00:03:20,120
- That's because you're a bird.
- Mickey?

12
00:03:21,760 --> 00:03:22,759
Leave me out of this.

13
00:03:22,760 --> 00:03:24,659
How can you say women are
more argumentative than men?

14
00:03:24,660 --> 00:03:26,679
- Because it's a well-known fact.
- No it is not. - See?

15
00:03:26,680 --> 00:03:30,838
- See what? - I mentioned that women
are more argumentative than men,

16
00:03:30,839 --> 00:03:32,339
and you've done nothing
but argue since.

17
00:03:32,340 --> 00:03:34,659
- I was discussing.
- What's the difference?

18
00:03:34,660 --> 00:03:37,299
One is arguing and the other one....

19
00:03:37,300 --> 00:03:38,699
isn't.

20
00:03:38,700 --> 00:03:41,459
Way to go, sis.
You baffled him with logic...

21
00:03:41,460 --> 00:03:44,619
He knows what I mean. Eddie,
do you think I'm argumentative?

22
00:03:44,620 --> 00:03:48,099
- You are a bit, yeah.
- No, I'm not. I wasn't arguing.

23
00:03:48,100 --> 00:03:49,739
No, she was discussing, you see.

24
00:03:49,740 --> 00:03:52,819
- Yeah, they do a lot of that, birds.
- Yeah, they do...mmm. Mmm.

25
00:03:52,820 --> 00:03:54,779
Oh, all right.

26
00:03:54,780 --> 00:03:58,539
You can be so annoying,
really...all of you.

27
00:03:58,540 --> 00:04:02,780
Well, looks like you were right,
he arrived last evening.

28
00:04:03,900 --> 00:04:05,220
Who did?

29
00:04:06,540 --> 00:04:08,380
Our new mark.

30
00:04:14,140 --> 00:04:16,539
Madani Wasem.

31
00:04:16,540 --> 00:04:19,659
Came to London in the '80s to
re-trace his father's footsteps

32
00:04:19,660 --> 00:04:21,619
and accept a place
at Oxford University.

33
00:04:21,620 --> 00:04:26,619
He graduated with a degree in
economics before returning

34
00:04:26,620 --> 00:04:30,299
to Bahrain to take his place on the
board of his father's company,

35
00:04:30,300 --> 00:04:32,619
The Gulf Partnership.

36
00:04:32,620 --> 00:04:36,980
Wasem was with friends when he heard
of his father's death five weeks ago.

37
00:04:41,660 --> 00:04:44,060
Yes! It's party time!

38
00:04:50,460 --> 00:04:52,939
So they didn't get on then?

39
00:04:52,940 --> 00:04:56,139
He'd lived his entire life
in his father's shadow.

40
00:04:56,140 --> 00:04:58,299
He was heard telling
an aide at the funeral

41
00:04:58,300 --> 00:05:00,939
that he'd spent his adult
life waiting for him to die.

42
00:05:00,940 --> 00:05:02,220
Oh, what a charmer.

43
00:05:02,221 --> 00:05:03,359
How much did he get?

44
00:05:03,360 --> 00:05:05,499
North of 850 million.

45
00:05:06,700 --> 00:05:09,539
He got the family money
and his father's shares,

46
00:05:09,540 --> 00:05:11,020
but he has no real power.

47
00:05:11,021 --> 00:05:13,979
His father was respected,
but he isn't.

48
00:05:13,980 --> 00:05:16,499
The board of Gulf Partnership
quickly closed ranks

49
00:05:16,500 --> 00:05:17,900
to stop him taking control.

50
00:05:17,901 --> 00:05:20,558
Which left Wasem with a bit
of a chip on his shoulder.

51
00:05:20,559 --> 00:05:21,859
Oh, poor love

52
00:05:21,860 --> 00:05:25,339
They see him for what
he is... Little more than a thug.

53
00:05:25,340 --> 00:05:28,019
He doesn't earn respect,
he buys it.

54
00:05:28,020 --> 00:05:30,539
Using his wealth to surround
himself with people

55
00:05:30,540 --> 00:05:32,020
who will do whatever he asks.

56
00:05:32,021 --> 00:05:37,800
Including an enforcer, someone who
will kill or torture on demand.

57
00:05:38,540 --> 00:05:42,299
The man who led the move
to stop Wasem taking control

58
00:05:42,300 --> 00:05:45,579
of his father's company was
found with his throat cut

59
00:05:45,580 --> 00:05:49,859
in his own bathroom by his 10-year-old
daughter, yesterday afternoon.

60
00:05:49,860 --> 00:05:52,779
Wasem has been linked
to two similar killings

61
00:05:52,780 --> 00:05:56,819
since his father's death, and
a long list of business associates

62
00:05:56,820 --> 00:05:59,578
being beaten and having
their families threatened.

63
00:05:59,579 --> 00:06:01,479
- Question.
- Go on.

64
00:06:01,480 --> 00:06:03,939
We usually spend our time staying
away from people like this.

65
00:06:03,940 --> 00:06:05,859
Why are we going after him?

66
00:06:05,860 --> 00:06:07,480
I think he's too good to pass up.

67
00:06:10,500 --> 00:06:14,099
He's been making his way around
Europe playing the markets.

68
00:06:14,100 --> 00:06:17,699
For anyone that openly opposes
him, he uses violence,

69
00:06:17,700 --> 00:06:20,859
but he knows that to take control
of his father's company, he has

70
00:06:20,860 --> 00:06:24,859
to prove to the shareholders he has
his father's flair for making money.

71
00:06:25,260 --> 00:06:31,019
So far he's played the markets
in Greece, Turkey, Spain,

72
00:06:31,020 --> 00:06:34,499
and Portugal, making a
hefty profit in each.

73
00:06:34,500 --> 00:06:37,699
Now he's in London, and he'll
be looking for a broker.

74
00:06:37,700 --> 00:06:39,899
Why travel?
You can buy shares anywhere.

75
00:06:39,900 --> 00:06:42,939
That's one of the lessons he
actually learnt from his father...

76
00:06:42,940 --> 00:06:45,459
local knowledge is the key
to making a good return.

77
00:06:45,460 --> 00:06:48,419
So he flies in, talks
to whoever he can,

78
00:06:48,420 --> 00:06:51,859
tries to find an inside track, and
then buys through a local broker.

79
00:06:51,860 --> 00:06:53,320
What kind of money
are we talking about?

80
00:06:53,339 --> 00:06:58,739
In Spain he invested
six million euros.

81
00:06:58,740 --> 00:07:02,099
He is very definitely high risk,
but with that comes high rewards.

82
00:07:02,100 --> 00:07:04,459
Well...I'm in.

83
00:07:04,460 --> 00:07:06,179
Ash?

84
00:07:06,180 --> 00:07:08,859
Well, you know me.
Where you go, I go.

85
00:07:08,860 --> 00:07:11,219
Albert?

86
00:07:11,220 --> 00:07:13,340
Yeah, all right.

87
00:07:14,380 --> 00:07:15,980
It would be rude not to.

88
00:07:17,500 --> 00:07:21,900
Good.
Then let's go get him.

89
00:07:24,700 --> 00:07:26,139
It is done.

90
00:07:26,140 --> 00:07:27,660
How?

91
00:07:28,700 --> 00:07:32,619
His throat cut from ear
to ear while he sat...

92
00:07:32,620 --> 00:07:33,820
in the restroom.

93
00:07:35,180 --> 00:07:36,420
Very appropriate.

94
00:07:38,220 --> 00:07:40,279
You know the last
thing he said to me

95
00:07:41,880 --> 00:07:43,839
was that my only chance

96
00:07:44,139 --> 00:07:46,739
of regaining my father's company...

97
00:07:47,940 --> 00:07:50,059
had gone down the toilet.

98
00:07:51,260 --> 00:07:52,979
There was a problem.

99
00:07:52,980 --> 00:07:55,899
His wife ran to a neighbour,
the police shut off the streets,

100
00:07:55,900 --> 00:07:58,259
- our enforcer was trapped.
- Was he arrested?

101
00:07:58,260 --> 00:08:01,819
No.
They shot him.

102
00:08:01,820 --> 00:08:03,420
He is dead.

103
00:08:05,100 --> 00:08:07,100
Replace him.

104
00:08:11,660 --> 00:08:13,420
So what's going on?

105
00:08:15,220 --> 00:08:16,659
Truth?

106
00:08:16,660 --> 00:08:18,379
Always.

107
00:08:18,380 --> 00:08:20,419
I'm tired, Albert.

108
00:08:20,420 --> 00:08:22,100
Take a break.

109
00:08:23,260 --> 00:08:26,979
I don't think a fortnight in Vegas
is gonna cure it this time.

110
00:08:26,980 --> 00:08:29,779
Well, so take a year...two.

111
00:08:29,780 --> 00:08:32,979
It's not that easy.
What about you?

112
00:08:32,980 --> 00:08:34,299
Ash?
Sean and Emma?

113
00:08:34,300 --> 00:08:38,539
We're all big enough
to take care of ourselves.

114
00:08:38,540 --> 00:08:41,419
No, we're a crew, a family.

115
00:08:41,519 --> 00:08:43,519
We don't walk out on each other.

116
00:08:44,220 --> 00:08:49,780
So this guy isn't just another mark?
He's your retirement fund?

117
00:08:52,740 --> 00:08:55,499
Marks like this one don't
come along very often.

118
00:08:55,500 --> 00:08:56,619
No they don't.

119
00:08:56,620 --> 00:09:01,019
So maybe everything we've done
has been leading us to this point.

120
00:09:01,020 --> 00:09:04,140
One big mark, our
very own lottery win.

121
00:09:05,340 --> 00:09:08,459
Then we can all walk away on
top, money in our pockets.

122
00:09:08,460 --> 00:09:10,220
He could kill you.

123
00:09:13,220 --> 00:09:16,300
Well, then we make that
a risk worth taking.

124
00:09:20,740 --> 00:09:23,139
Oh, Emma, shopping list.

125
00:09:23,140 --> 00:09:24,380
Oo, my kind of job.

126
00:09:24,381 --> 00:09:27,079
Anything new there Em?

127
00:09:27,080 --> 00:09:30,179
Yeah. His favourite buys are gas
and oil, but he hates new media,

128
00:09:30,180 --> 00:09:32,459
pharmaceuticals,
retail companies.

129
00:09:32,460 --> 00:09:35,238
What he loves best
is an edge, something

130
00:09:35,239 --> 00:09:36,339
that sets him ahead
from everybody else.

131
00:09:36,340 --> 00:09:38,499
Then that's exactly
what we'll give him.

132
00:09:38,999 --> 00:09:41,399
Sean, let's see how long we've
got, he's got a private plane,

133
00:09:41,400 --> 00:09:43,819
but check with the service see
when he's due to leave.

134
00:09:43,820 --> 00:09:45,180
- Yeah, gotcha.
- How are things going?

135
00:09:45,181 --> 00:09:47,659
It's going live now,
bank account's set up,

136
00:09:47,660 --> 00:09:51,339
- I'm still working on the hardware
but I think I can crack it. - Great.

137
00:09:51,340 --> 00:09:53,220
We're in.

138
00:09:56,540 --> 00:09:59,940
Yeah. No, no, no.
Sure...

139
00:10:00,980 --> 00:10:04,699
No, listen, we wait. We wait until
New York opens in the morning,

140
00:10:04,700 --> 00:10:08,699
because if the Dow Jones rallies
we'll get more action here.

141
00:10:08,700 --> 00:10:13,020
Yeah. My clients have very specific
targets with zero risk attached.

142
00:10:14,220 --> 00:10:16,579
Yes, I said zero.

143
00:10:16,580 --> 00:10:21,059
No, but listen, we wait...we wait
until the very last moment,

144
00:10:21,060 --> 00:10:24,579
and then we buy fast before anyone
else gets wind of what we're buying.

145
00:10:24,580 --> 00:10:27,019
No-one else in London
will get close.

146
00:10:27,020 --> 00:10:29,060
All right, call you later.
Bye.

147
00:10:30,460 --> 00:10:33,458
- It's too much.
- Would you relax!

148
00:10:33,459 --> 00:10:35,859
This is still peanuts. We could
move up to ten million

149
00:10:35,860 --> 00:10:37,399
before anyone else
starts asking questions.

150
00:10:37,400 --> 00:10:41,139
Well, I'm not so sure.
I think it's all happening too fast.

151
00:10:41,140 --> 00:10:44,438
What if they realise why
we buy what we do?

152
00:10:44,439 --> 00:10:45,939
They won't.
How could they?

153
00:10:45,940 --> 00:10:49,580
Relax. Breathe! Have some wine,
try the T-bone, it's to die for.

154
00:11:10,500 --> 00:11:13,059
- Gentlemen, forgive me.
- Yes?

155
00:11:13,060 --> 00:11:15,739
My employer, Madani Wasem,
was on the next table

156
00:11:15,740 --> 00:11:18,859
and couldn't help overhear you
talking about your business.

157
00:11:18,860 --> 00:11:21,940
You trade on the London
stock markets, no?

158
00:11:23,540 --> 00:11:26,779
I'm sorry... Why are we having
this conversation?

159
00:11:26,780 --> 00:11:29,459
Mr Wasem is in London
for a short time,

160
00:11:29,460 --> 00:11:33,019
and he would like to invite you
to visit him at his hotel.

161
00:11:33,020 --> 00:11:37,540
He believes you may find such
a visit to be mutually beneficial.

162
00:11:40,900 --> 00:11:42,539
He said what!?

163
00:11:42,540 --> 00:11:45,339
That he did not do home visits

164
00:11:45,340 --> 00:11:50,420
and should you wish to talk to him
then to do so during office hours.

165
00:11:56,700 --> 00:11:59,199
Did you tell this "William Cole"
who I was?

166
00:11:59,200 --> 00:12:01,579
- Yes, sir.
- And?

167
00:12:01,580 --> 00:12:04,420
He said that he had
heard of your father.

168
00:12:10,580 --> 00:12:13,339
There's a fine line between
piquing someone's interest

169
00:12:13,340 --> 00:12:17,019
- and being so rude they never want
to set eyes on you again. - True.

170
00:12:17,020 --> 00:12:19,979
- But do you think he'll call?
- He's a bully.

171
00:12:19,980 --> 00:12:22,899
It upsets him when people don't do
what he wants them to do.

172
00:12:22,900 --> 00:12:24,539
Evening, all.

173
00:12:24,540 --> 00:12:26,899
- What's that?
- What's what?

174
00:12:26,900 --> 00:12:28,659
- The cable.
- What cable?

175
00:12:28,660 --> 00:12:31,339
Oh this! Oh! Well, it depends
on how you look at it.

176
00:12:31,340 --> 00:12:35,059
To the untrained eye, this is just a
length of fibre-optic cable.

177
00:12:35,060 --> 00:12:38,259
But in the right hands and
with a bit of razzle dazzle,

178
00:12:38,260 --> 00:12:41,660
this is the beating heart
of the British economy.

179
00:12:43,340 --> 00:12:44,420
He called yet?

180
00:12:54,460 --> 00:12:57,540
Playing hard to get never
worked for me either.

181
00:13:04,020 --> 00:13:07,540
We've found a London broker who
can oversee all our purchases.

182
00:13:16,220 --> 00:13:18,420
OK, I think we might
need a boost.

183
00:13:29,980 --> 00:13:32,379
Bloody marvellous, the
man's a miracle worker.

184
00:13:32,380 --> 00:13:36,019
Invested 40k, got a 60%
return inside of three days.

185
00:13:36,020 --> 00:13:38,819
- That's incredible. - Someone
must be giving him an edge.

186
00:13:38,820 --> 00:13:42,059
- What's his name again?
- Cole. William Cole.

187
00:13:42,060 --> 00:13:46,099
- Don't they call him "Golden Balls"
or such like? - That's the chappie.

188
00:13:46,100 --> 00:13:47,359
Can you get me in to see him?

189
00:13:47,360 --> 00:13:49,059
Well, I'll try, old son,
but he's quite exclusive.

190
00:13:49,860 --> 00:13:52,540
Mind you, not hard to see why.

191
00:14:02,780 --> 00:14:06,619
You won't make it ring
by looking at it.

192
00:14:06,620 --> 00:14:08,140
Maybe I called it wrong.

193
00:14:09,660 --> 00:14:11,180
No, you're just wound up.

194
00:14:12,500 --> 00:14:14,900
I mean, most of the time,
when a mark's just a mark,

195
00:14:14,901 --> 00:14:18,659
you get a set-back, you don't panic,
you take it in your stride.

196
00:14:18,660 --> 00:14:21,580
It's only cos this one's
more important.

197
00:14:22,980 --> 00:14:24,220
Sorry, I don't get you.

198
00:14:27,300 --> 00:14:29,939
How long have I known you, Mick?

199
00:14:29,940 --> 00:14:32,699
- 20 years? - And in all that time,
you've played the odds.

200
00:14:32,700 --> 00:14:36,260
Avoided marks like this Wasem
bloke like the plague.

201
00:14:37,780 --> 00:14:39,779
So I figure if that's
no longer the case,

202
00:14:39,780 --> 00:14:41,979
then either you've got a
death wish, in which case

203
00:14:41,980 --> 00:14:44,079
I'm not sure why you have
to take me with you.

204
00:14:44,980 --> 00:14:48,660
Or...he's a special kind of mark.

205
00:14:49,700 --> 00:14:53,460
The kind of mark who'll give you enough
money to get out of the game forever.

206
00:14:57,900 --> 00:14:59,859
Am I that easy to read?

207
00:14:59,860 --> 00:15:01,499
Yeah, a doddle, always have been.

208
00:15:01,500 --> 00:15:03,779
I should have known.
You can't kid a kidder.

209
00:15:03,780 --> 00:15:05,979
No, that's bollocks.

210
00:15:05,980 --> 00:15:09,860
You can kid anyone...
Except a mate.

211
00:15:11,460 --> 00:15:15,019
Whatever you do is all right
with me. Do you mean that?

212
00:15:15,020 --> 00:15:18,339
I wouldn't have said it otherwise.

213
00:15:18,340 --> 00:15:21,739
Just don't start getting all
soppy on me, all right?

214
00:15:21,740 --> 00:15:25,139
Anyway, I'm not getting any younger
and I'm fed up of carrying you.

215
00:15:25,140 --> 00:15:26,740
Well, yes. Yeah.

216
00:15:28,180 --> 00:15:31,700
Although none of this makes a blind
bit of difference if he doesn't call.

217
00:16:13,220 --> 00:16:14,500
Time for plan B?

218
00:16:19,300 --> 00:16:21,059
William Cole.

219
00:16:21,060 --> 00:16:24,299
Mr Cole, this is Madani Wasem.

220
00:16:24,300 --> 00:16:26,100
Let me check my diary.

221
00:16:28,660 --> 00:16:30,300
No, sorry, I can't do noon.

222
00:16:31,780 --> 00:16:33,700
Yeah, yeah, I can do 12.30.

223
00:16:36,900 --> 00:16:39,300
OK, yeah, see you then.

224
00:18:02,140 --> 00:18:04,459
Yeah, it's me.
We're in.

225
00:18:04,460 --> 00:18:05,820
Thank you, Emma.

226
00:18:07,580 --> 00:18:11,100
I swear that girl could scam a space
shuttle if she set her mind to it.

227
00:18:14,980 --> 00:18:17,739
You know, long before "con"
became a dirty word,

228
00:18:17,740 --> 00:18:20,859
all it stood for was "confidence".

229
00:18:20,860 --> 00:18:23,099
And what's so bad about that?

230
00:18:23,100 --> 00:18:27,739
Now, I'm not saying that all my
peers are angels, far from it!

231
00:18:27,740 --> 00:18:31,019
But whatever industry you work in,
be it an office, or a hospital,

232
00:18:31,020 --> 00:18:34,139
or a road gang I guarantee you'll
have your share of rogues too.

233
00:18:34,140 --> 00:18:37,699
We're criminals because
we work outside the law.

234
00:18:37,700 --> 00:18:42,500
Fine. But what we do, we
can't do without greed.

235
00:18:44,180 --> 00:18:48,539
Take Madani Wasem for instance.
Now, he could buy his stocks

236
00:18:48,540 --> 00:18:50,439
and his shares just
like everyone else.

237
00:18:50,440 --> 00:18:51,539
Pay the same price,

238
00:18:51,540 --> 00:18:54,739
take the same risk. If he did,
there's no way we could touch him.

239
00:18:54,740 --> 00:18:57,258
Honestly, do you think
we could do what we do

240
00:18:57,259 --> 00:18:58,459
if he wasn't looking for an edge?

241
00:18:58,460 --> 00:19:00,478
If he wasn't looking
for something that gave

242
00:19:00,479 --> 00:19:02,779
him an unfair advantage
over everyone else?

243
00:19:02,780 --> 00:19:06,539
